<urn:usf:artefact:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform> a <urn:usf:ontology:Artefact>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "semanticcontractauthenticationplatform";
    <urn:usf:ontology:artefactKind> <urn:usf:artefactkind:contract>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalPath> "contracts/semantic/authenticationplatform.json";
    <urn:usf:ontology:governedByPathRule> <urn:usf:pathrule:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:generatedByComponent> <urn:usf:generator:semanticcontract>.
<urn:usf:pathrule:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform> a <urn:usf:ontology:PathRule>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "semanticcontractauthenticationplatform";
    <urn:usf:ontology:pathPattern> "contracts/semantic/authenticationplatform.json".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingArtefactPlan> <urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingEquivalenceRule> <urn:usf:equivalencerule:semanticcontractprojection>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform>, <urn:usf:artefact:semanticcontractauthenticationplatform>, <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformlifecycle>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformlifecycle> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Spans the full platform sign-in surface: login initiates a PKCE/state/nonce redirect handoff, the callback validates state/code/nonce and resolves identity into a server-side session, session reads return authenticated or unauthenticated context, and logout idempotently destroys session and clears host-only plus domain-scoped cookies. It also covers IdP and policy administration lifecycles (list/create/update/rotate-secret/enable/disable/delete identity providers, OIDC discovery import, and read/validate/write of MFA, lockout, session, and claim-mapping policy). Each administrative mutation resolves the tenant credential, audits, then writes to the identity provider and may be read back.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformstatemodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformstatemodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Authentication state moves unauthenticated -> authenticating -> authenticated or denied, materialised as a session record carrying session id, user id, tenant and organisation id, roles, resolved permission bundle, display name, and expiry, with no-membership and system-admin sessions holding empty tenant context by design. Administrative state includes per-tenant identity-provider definitions (alias, enabled, masked secret, scopes, issuer/JWKS validation result), OIDC discovery validation states, MFA mode (none/optional/required with TOTP or WebAuthn), lockout thresholds, and session lifespan policy. Custom-domain callback derivation depends on a domain's verified-and-active state, falling back to the platform realm for inactive or unknown hosts.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformpermissions>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformpermissions> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The login/session path establishes the actor rather than requiring a permission, converting resolved roles into an explicit permission bundle where tenant roles come from membership and system-admin comes from realm roles without tenant membership. All authentication-administration routes are tenant-scoped and require read or write auth-settings permission with the matching admin scope, resolving the tenant credential from the FQDN-derived tenant context so one tenant can never read or mutate another tenant's provider, policy, or mapping configuration. Custom-domain callback eligibility is gated by tenant domain-write lifecycle operations.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformcontracts>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformcontracts> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The operation surface covers login initiation, provider-callback handling, logout, server-side session lookup, an internal forward-auth check, and provider enumeration, plus tenant-scoped administration operations for identity-provider list/create/update/delete, OIDC discovery import, callback-URL derivation, non-interactive connection test, claim/role mapping read and full-replacement write, and MFA/lockout/session policy read and write. Mutations return a no-content success and reads return redacted projections; provider secrets and raw tokens are never exposed across the contract.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformvalidation>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformvalidation> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Login sanitises the return-to target, emits PKCE challenge parameters, binds the callback to the pre-auth cookie, and rejects missing or unknown state/code and provider error callbacks while accepting only stored session cookies. Administrative validation enforces provider allowlists, required and safe-scheme OIDC URLs, reserved-alias rules, discovery issuer and JWKS validity (allowing plain HTTP only for local hosts), MFA enum values, positive lockout thresholds, bounded session lifespans, non-dangerous claim names, and realm roles restricted to the tenant-role allowlist; secrets are preserved when omitted on update and invalid bodies stop before any audit or provider mutation.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformerrormodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformerrormodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "All failures are fail-closed: an unauthenticated session lookup returns an unauthenticated/401 result, callback failures redirect to the login page with a generic sign-in error, and session-store lookup failure falls through to unauthenticated without leaking provider detail. Administrative failures map to typed outcomes such as validation error, no-tenant, no-credential, invalid-credential, forbidden-realm-operation, realm-unreachable, not-found, issuer-mismatch, JWKS-invalid, unreachable, and invalid-document; provider failure returns a typed degraded/readiness result, keeps mutation boundaries closed, and never fabricates successful provider state, and inactive or unknown custom hosts degrade to the platform realm rather than being trusted.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformauditmodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformauditmodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Login and session creation are represented by authentication events and session-store state, and logout removes session state, while read-only session lookup and discovery validation carry no mutation audit. Every administrative mutation (provider create/update/delete/test, MFA, lockout, session, and claim-mapping changes) emits an audit-before-change event recording alias, operation, changed field names, and secret-changed booleans only; configuration and secret values are never audited, and audit failure aborts the mutation before the provider is touched.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformreadinessmodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformreadinessmodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Readiness for the live session path depends on identity-provider, session-store, and configuration availability, with an explicit deterministic fixture mode for tests; administrative readiness is credential-derived and only reports configured/ok when the tenant realm credential can read and mutate policies, otherwise classifying missing-credential, invalid-credential, forbidden-realm-operation, realm-unreachable, or discovery-invalid rather than hiding them. Degraded mode disables provider-dependent mutation paths while keeping read-only readiness and audit visible, and real brokered/interactive IdP login is carried as externally limited rather than fake-passed.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformproof>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformproof> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Substrate and unit proofs cover login routes, the auth usecase, session fixtures, cookie security, token crypto, role/permission resolution, and audit-first ordering, while runtime proofs validate live identity-provider settings round-trips, IdP CRUD with secret rotation and redaction, OIDC discovery/JWKS/callback/test-connection, MFA and session policy write/read-back/restore, the claim-mapping semantic journey, and custom-domain callback derivation against local substrate. Proof is hermetic/runtime lineage; current activation evidence is recorded by the contract proof result and remains subject to freshness and invalidation.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:authenticationplatformsemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformuisemantics>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:authenticationplatformuisemantics> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The authenticationplatform capability has one framework-neutral UI semantic model with explicit surfaces, view models, components, journeys, permissions, accessibility, localisation, and target-specific renderer contracts. This semantic closure disclaims product parity, human acceptance, accessibility compliance, and launch-language readiness.".
<urn:usf:semanticcontract:authenticationplatform> <urn:usf:ontology:disclaims> <urn:usf:nonclaim:nohumanacceptance>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:nouiproductparity>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:noaccessibilitycompliance>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:nolaunchi18n>.
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> a <urn:usf:ontology:SourceSemanticBinding>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource";
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingSource> <urn:usf:sourceartefact:s0690349d8d30f17a43ec8f980edbfd6944da371207d0ab1d8a1dfab15e6ce5d7>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:semanticcontract:backgroundworkersjobrunner>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingContentDigest> "ca2d6b90977582bef7a01b24ca5e8b6402b1914f1e19547e2c383b4a5bd32cd5";
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingPath> "spec/instances/semantic-contract/background-workers-job-runner.json";
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingEquivalenceKind> <urn:usf:equivalencekind:structural>.
<urn:usf:semanticcontract:backgroundworkersjobrunner> <urn:usf:ontology:semanticLifecycleState> <urn:usf:semanticlifecyclestate:active>.
<urn:usf:repository:foundation> <urn:usf:ontology:hasArtefactPlan> <urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>.
<urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner> a <urn:usf:ontology:ArtefactPlan>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner";
    <urn:usf:ontology:ownedByRepository> <urn:usf:repository:foundation>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:plansArtefact> <urn:usf:artefact:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:plansSemanticResource> <urn:usf:semanticcontract:backgroundworkersjobrunner>.
<urn:usf:artefact:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner> a <urn:usf:ontology:Artefact>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner";
    <urn:usf:ontology:artefactKind> <urn:usf:artefactkind:contract>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalPath> "contracts/semantic/backgroundworkersjobrunner.json";
    <urn:usf:ontology:governedByPathRule> <urn:usf:pathrule:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:generatedByComponent> <urn:usf:generator:semanticcontract>.
<urn:usf:pathrule:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner> a <urn:usf:ontology:PathRule>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:canonicalName> "semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner";
    <urn:usf:ontology:pathPattern> "contracts/semantic/backgroundworkersjobrunner.json".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingArtefactPlan> <urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingEquivalenceRule> <urn:usf:equivalencerule:semanticcontractprojection>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:artefactplan:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>, <urn:usf:artefact:semanticcontractbackgroundworkersjobrunner>, <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerlifecycle>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerlifecycle> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "A worker emits a heartbeat to mark itself alive, claims a pending event from the event substrate, runs its registered handler, marks the event processed, idempotently skips events already processed, retries a failing handler, dead-letters the event once maxAttempts is reached, and exposes its liveness. The runner consumes the durable-queue records produced by the event bus and applies retry, dead-letter, and redrive-compatible semantics so deferred work executes exactly-effectively once. Provider failure degrades readiness and keeps mutation boundaries closed rather than processing unsafely.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerstatemodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerstatemodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "State comprises workerId, workerKind, a heartbeat timestamp, liveness in alive|stale|stopped, the status of the claimed event, a retry count, and the dead-letter transition; the runner does not own tenant records and reads pending and dead-letter queues from the event-bus state model. Idempotency is anchored on the event's processed status so a re-delivered or reclaimed event is not processed twice. Liveness is derived from heartbeat age rather than stored as a separate authoritative flag.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerpermissions>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerpermissions> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The only external surface, GET /api/admin/workers, is global and requires platform.workers.read; event processing itself is server-internal and is not callable by tenant UI. Workers therefore expose operational liveness to operators only and never offer direct tenant-triggered job execution. Tenant context on processed events is preserved through the event records the worker claims.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnercontracts>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnercontracts> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The external contract is GET /api/admin/workers, backed by an internal processNext handler registry and the JobRunnerPort with its PostgresJobAdapter; the event bus supplies the pending and dead-letter queues the runner consumes. Processing is expressed as claiming and completing event-bus records, so the worker contract composes with the event-bus contract rather than defining its own delivery semantics. The port seam keeps the job-execution provider swappable.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnervalidation>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnervalidation> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Worker processing only claims pending events, never reclaims an already-processed event, honours maxAttempts before dead-lettering, and records a heartbeat for the supplied worker id and kind. Idempotent skip of processed events is the core invariant that prevents duplicate side effects under retry or redelivery. These behaviours are exercised by the event-worker runtime proof.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnererrormodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnererrormodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Outcomes are deterministic and fail closed: a handler error becomes a retry or, at maxAttempts, a dead-letter; an unavailable Postgres substrate causes an honest proof skip or readiness failure; and stale or stopped workers are explicit liveness states rather than hidden errors. Degraded mode disables the processing paths that depend on the Postgres adapter while keeping read-only readiness visible, and no path fabricates a processed result.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerauditmodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerauditmodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Heartbeats are operational telemetry and are not audit events; the auditable actions in this domain (operator redrive and related operations) are emitted by the event capability rather than by the worker. This keeps the worker's high-frequency liveness signal out of the privileged-action audit trail while still leaving redrive and operator actions auditable upstream.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerreadinessmodel>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerreadinessmodel> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Readiness is worker heartbeat liveness (alive|stale|stopped) together with the event-processing proof; a failure to claim, process, or dead-letter is a proof and readiness failure rather than a silent stall. Readiness degrades explicitly when the substrate is unavailable and never upgrades a production-shaped state to production-live. Liveness states are surfaced rather than masked so stale or stopped workers are visible to operators.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerproof>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunnerproof> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:complete>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "Behaviour is grounded in the event-worker runtime proof, which validates live Postgres claim, process, idempotent skip, retry, dead-letter, and heartbeat (level-4 live substrate validation), captured here as informational semantic lineage from the USF coverage record and equivalence audit with no source import and an open implementation language. The proof expectation is the lineage evidence, not a current USF readiness verdict. Proof is hermetic/runtime lineage; current activation evidence is recorded by the contract proof result and remains subject to freshness and invalidation.".
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backgroundworkersjobrunnersemanticsource> <urn:usf:ontology:sourceBindingTarget> <urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunneruisemantics>.
<urn:usf:contractfacet:backgroundworkersjobrunneruisemantics> <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatus> <urn:usf:facetstatus:notapplicable>;
    <urn:usf:ontology:facetStatement> "The backgroundworkersjobrunner capability is explicitly internal; no product or operator UI is authorised. Any UI requires a deliberate exposure amendment.".
<urn:usf:semanticcontract:backgroundworkersjobrunner> <urn:usf:ontology:disclaims> <urn:usf:nonclaim:nohumanacceptance>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:nouiproductparity>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:noaccessibilitycompliance>, <urn:usf:nonclaim:nolaunchi18n>.
<urn:usf:sourcesemanticbinding:backupandrestoresemanticsource> a <urn:usf:ontology:SourceSemanticBinding>;
